%2F20%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2=
F20%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df=
6c60617da42abd12a )
found that a majority of registered voters=E2=80=9453 percent=E2=80=94disap=
prove of =E2=80=9Cbusinessman Elon Musk playing a prominent role in the Tru=
mp administration.=E2=80=9D That disapproval rating is even higher among in=
dependents, while only 41 percent of voters approve of Musk=E2=80=99s invol=
vement.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Those poll numbers, I suspect, will only get worse once the Trump administr=
ation gets underway. I also don=E2=80=99t need a poll to know that
Zuckerberg is someone that no normal American would want to hang out with a=
t a party. Nor would they want to awkwardly chit-chat with Altman about lar=
ge language models or share a bottle of Chenin Blanc with the hosts of the =
All-In podcast and gab about their funds. It=E2=80=99s an even safer bet th=
at none of the tech barons onstage with Trump today, nor most of the people=
 invited to the best parties in Washington this weekend, would ever choose =
to spend time in Council Bluffs or Johnstown or
Toledo or any corner of =E2=80=9Cforgotten America=E2=80=9D that Trump has =
sworn to protect.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Trump=E2=80=99s diminished opponents don=E2=80=99t have much to work with t=
hese days. But flanked by Bezos and Zuck and Musk, the new president gifted=
 them an image to use, if they so choose: a government of the wealthy, by t=
he wealthy, for the wealthy. It=E2=80=99s the kind of thing that would have=
 once been dismissed as a conspiracy=E2=80=94the
smoke-filled room where rich plutocrats huddled with politicians to plot th=
eir next moves, the country be damned. But here it was, in plain view insid=
e the Capitol Rotunda.

President Biden left office this week without much credibility left, but hi=
s last-minute warning about a coming oligarchy now doesn=E2=80=99t seem off=
-base, even if most of the oligarchs are rich nerds. If Democrats weren=E2=
=80=99t so transparently spooked by young people=E2=80=99s addiction to Tik=
Tok, they could make
a political issue out of Trump and Chew colluding in broad daylight to prot=
ect a massive profit-driven corporation, in what appears to be one of the m=
ost corrupt handshake deals in the history of the United States. But that w=
ould require some truth-telling and bravery from a party that, right now, i=
s afraid of its own tiny shadow.

