ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">No matter how smashing his victory, as I
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dVaHZqT0JlQjBlSDcwRjN0QVVGST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdHJ=
1bXBzLXNlY29uZC10ZXJtLW5lZWQtZm9yLXNwZWVkLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJT=
I2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMjAlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0b=
V9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MSUy=
RjIwJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbC=
I6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMzUwMTB9/996b801e913819616cdc=
5a6028f3be4589be9e323306e099760120251fec2b70" style=3D"text-decoration:unde=
rline;color:#d40000;">wrote</a> a few weeks ago, Trump notably remains a on=
e-term president with a midterm election coming up next year. The new presi=
dent may indeed usher in a =E2=80=9Cgolden age of America,=E2=80=9D as he p=
romised Monday at the Capitol, but he only has a limited window of time to =
establish this new epoch of <em>winning</em>. It=E2=80=99s worth noting tha=
t as he takes office, like any incoming president, Trump is
probably at the peak of his powers. His favorable rating as he returns to o=
ffice is at an <em>all-time high</em>=E2=80=94but that high is just 46 perc=
ent. More Americans=E2=80=9448 percent=E2=80=94continue to have an unfavora=
ble view of the president.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
"><br/>The harem of billionaires that Trump put on display on Monday was in=
tended as a flex. But I thought it was a curious public relations gambit, a=
 dangerous self-own for a president supposedly aligned with the common man,
people who didn=E2=80=99t go to college and work with their hands. With apo=
logies to <strong>Luigi Mangione</strong>, most Americans don=E2=80=99t ref=
lexively hate billionaires in the way that <strong>Elizabeth Warren</strong=
> and <strong>Bernie Sanders </strong>think they do. But it=E2=80=99s a tim=
eless political truth that voters are skeptical of powerful corporations, t=
he whiff of corruption, and a government that doles out favors to privilege=
d insiders over the public. Any poll will tell you that, no matter who is
president.=C2=A0<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Inde=
ed, there is already some suspicion among the electorate about how Trump mi=
ght reward all these C.E.O.s scrumming to get at his teat=E2=80=94especiall=
y when it comes to Musk, the world=E2=80=99s richest man, who has been foll=
owing the new president around like a middle schooler with a crush since at=
 least October. A <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6Im=
RnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVaHZqT0JlQjBlSDcwRjN0QVVGST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6L=
y9wb2xsLnF1LmVkdS9wb2xsLXJlbGVhc2U_cmVsZWFzZWlkPTM5MTdcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY2FtcGFp=
Z249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMjAlMkY=
yNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0=
NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MSUyRjIwJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1M=
DAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQx=
MmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwNDg5NTR9/3a=
1c883081d2eab7cb29e5dd8c6f4bef5b57da01a0d30ac40961ba6ad2236add" style=3D"te=
xt-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">Quinnipiac poll</a>
found that a majority of registered voters=E2=80=9453 percent=E2=80=94disap=
prove of =E2=80=9Cbusinessman Elon Musk playing a prominent role in the Tru=
mp administration.=E2=80=9D That disapproval rating is even higher among in=
dependents, while only 41 percent of voters approve of Musk=E2=80=99s invol=
vement.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Those poll numbers, I suspect, will only =
get worse once the Trump administration gets underway. I also don=E2=80=99t=
 need a poll to know that
Zuckerberg is someone that no normal American would want to hang out with a=
t a party. Nor would they want to awkwardly chit-chat with Altman about lar=
ge language models or share a bottle of Chenin Blanc with the hosts of the =
<em>All-In</em> podcast and gab about their funds. It=E2=80=99s an even saf=
er bet that none of the tech barons onstage with Trump today, nor most of t=
he people invited to the best parties in Washington this weekend, would eve=
r choose to spend time in Council Bluffs or Johnstown or
Toledo or any corner of =E2=80=9Cforgotten America=E2=80=9D that Trump has =
sworn to protect.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump=E2=80=99s diminished oppo=
nents don=E2=80=99t have much to work with these days. But flanked by Bezos=
 and Zuck and Musk, the new president gifted them an image to use, if they =
so choose: a government of the wealthy, by the wealthy, for the wealthy. It=
=E2=80=99s the kind of thing that would have once been dismissed as a consp=
iracy=E2=80=94the
smoke-filled room where rich plutocrats huddled with politicians to plot th=
eir next moves, the country be damned. But here it was, in plain view insid=
e the Capitol Rotunda.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;">President Biden =
left office this week without much credibility left, but his last-minute wa=
rning about a coming oligarchy now doesn=E2=80=99t seem off-base, even if m=
ost of the oligarchs are rich nerds. If Democrats weren=E2=80=99t so transp=
arently spooked by young people=E2=80=99s addiction to TikTok, they could m=
ake
a political issue out of Trump and Chew colluding in broad daylight to prot=
ect a massive profit-driven corporation, in what appears to be one of the m=
ost corrupt handshake deals in the history of the United States. But that w=
ould require some truth-telling and bravery from a party that, right now, i=
s afraid of its own tiny shadow.</p></div>
